<dl id="n47153c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n47" href="#n47153c">N47 (VI.B.40)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n47all.htm#n47153c"> 153(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> sacred spit = C. / creation, pact / compliance <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n47153c"><li>FW 516.33 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/lexrA.htm#n47153c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/l39rA.htm#n47153c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n47153c">MS missing</ms> </li><li>JJA not reproduced <a name="rAd10ydash" href="../../ff/fdra/rda.htm#rAd10ydash">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rA/rAd10.htm#n47153c">Draft: III&sect;3A.10</a>+'&apos;</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">In line 8 of Chapter CII appears to be mentioned the curious custom of spitting, as a sign of healing and blessing, which was common among several peoples of Africa in Budge&apos;s day. Among the Masai, for instance, spitting was considered creative, and complimentary to him spat upon, and bargains were sealed with a spit. <small> E.A. Wallis Budge, <a name="BOD3" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BOD3"><cite title="source">The Book of the Dead</cite></a>, 2nd Ed (1909) cxlv</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Transferred via <a name="sh6008d" href="sh6all.htm#sh6008d">Sheet vi-08(d)</a> </mm> </dd></dl>
